{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:16:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:16:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20970"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20970"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.91,0.05,0.01,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100037"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13845"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82429"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"125"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43736"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100037"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of low back pain after gardening over the weekend. The pain is localised to her lower back without radiation to her legs. She reports difficulty getting out of bed and getting dressed due to the pain. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works as an office administrator and has taken two days off work due to the pain. She is concerned that movement will worsen her condition and has been resting in bed since the pain started.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has tenderness over the lumbar paraspinal muscles bilaterally without midline tenderness. Straight leg raise is negative bilaterally. She has normal power, sensation, and reflexes in both lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Remain active with modified activities as tolerated","Avoid all bending and twisting movements for two weeks","Remain off work until pain completely resolves","Complete bed rest for one week","Restrict all physical activity until review in one week"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute non-specific low back pain without any red flags suggesting serious pathology. The absence of neurological symptoms, normal neurological examination, and mechanism of injury are consistent with a musculoskeletal cause of pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemain active with modified activities as tolerated\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management advice based on high-quality evidence (NHMRC Level 1 Evidence). Research consistently shows that staying active improves pain relief, functional outcomes, reduces sick leave, and enables earlier return to work compared to bed rest. Activity may need to be modified temporarily by changing duration, intensity, frequency, or technique, but complete avoidance of activity is not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete bed rest for one week\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for acute low back pain. Evidence shows that the longer a person stays in bed due to low back pain, the worse their ability to function and return to work becomes. Prolonged bed rest can lead to deconditioning, muscle weakness, and potentially worsen outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid all bending and twisting movements for two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive. While certain movements might temporarily exacerbate pain, patients should be encouraged to gradually resume normal movement patterns with modifications as needed. Complete avoidance of these movements for an extended period may lead to fear-avoidance behaviors and delayed recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemain off work until pain completely resolves\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate advice. Early return to work, possibly with modified duties if necessary, is associated with better outcomes. Waiting for complete pain resolution before returning to work can unnecessarily prolong disability and may contribute to chronicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestrict all physical activity until review in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is too restrictive and contradicts evidence-based recommendations. Physical activity should be encouraged rather than restricted, with appropriate modifications to accommodate pain levels. Restricting all physical activity may reinforce unhelpful beliefs about pain and movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Staying active rather than bed rest is recommended for acute low back pain of less than six weeks duration.","Patients with low back pain should be reassured that pain exacerbation during activity is not a sign of damage.","Activity modification rather than complete rest leads to better long-term outcomes for acute low back pain."],"references":["Parr A, Askin G. Non-radicular low back pain: Assessment and evidence-based treatment. Aust J Gen Pract. 2020 Nov;49(11):724-727. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-06-20-5476. PMID: 33123711. Accessed at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/november/non-radicular-low-back-pain","O\u0027Keeffe, M, and Michaleff, Z. RACGP Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions: Advice to stay active for people with acute low back pain. Published October 2013, Last updated: September 2019. Accessed at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/a/advice-to-stay-active-for-people-with-back-pain"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82429"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20970"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82429"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T21:15:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T06:53:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13845"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100037"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdA